  </div></section>

  <section class="section"><div class="wrap">
    <h2>Common Miele MasterCool failures our techs see in LA</h2>
    <div class="fail-block"><h3>F7 / F0 / F1 / F11 temperature sensor error codes</h3><p>Miele error-code specificity: F7 refrigerator sensor, F0 freezer sensor, F1 ambient, F11 evaporator. NTC sensor drift at 5-8 year mark. Sensor swap $240–$320; always clear codes post-repair.</p></div>
    <div class="fail-block"><h3>Ice maker not producing — water valve or module</h3><p>Standard ice-maker diagnostic. Water inlet valve $260–$360, ice-maker module $340–$480, water filter restriction check (6-month replacement).</p></div>
    <div class="fail-block"><h3>Door gasket compression loss — European seal profile</h3><p>European-spec gasket profile different from US-standard. Compression loss at 10-15 yr causes warm temps + excessive cycling. Per-section gasket $300–$440.</p></div>
    <div class="fail-block"><h3>MasterCool app / Wi-Fi connectivity</h3><p>Miele@home network connectivity issues — router 2.4GHz / 5GHz compatibility, app re-pair, firmware update. Most resolve at reconfiguration; rare Wi-Fi module failure $300–$440.</p></div>
    <div class="fail-block"><h3>Control board on legacy electronic generations</h3><p>2005-2015 generation Miele electronic controls occasionally require board replacement. Main control board $460–$680; display board $340–$500.</p></div>
    <div class="fail-block"><h3>Integrated panel-ready service discipline</h3><p>Custom-cabinetry panel protection during any exterior-adjacent service. European-specification finishes restoration-complex; interior work access preferred.</p></div>
  </div></section>

  <section class="section alt"><div class="wrap narrow">
    <h2>Miele family continuity — Gütersloh 1899 to Alabama 2025</h2>
    <p>Miele was founded in 1899 by Carl Miele and Reinhard Zinkann in Herzebrock, Germany; the company relocated to Gütersloh in 1907 and has been headquartered there for 118+ years. The Miele and Zinkann families retain full private ownership into the 4th generation — highly unusual for a 125-year industrial manufacturer at Miele's global scale. The family-ownership structure has preserved engineering-continuity priorities — long-service-life product design, conservative material choices, and parts-support commitments on legacy platforms — that differ meaningfully from private-equity-owned or public-company-owned luxury appliance brands.</p>
    <p>In 2023 Miele announced a new manufacturing plant in Leeds, Alabama — the company's first US manufacturing facility, scheduled to come online 2025. The plant represents Miele's largest US investment to date and is expected to shorten parts lead times for some product lines over the 2025-2027 transition period. Current Miele parts for MasterCool + residential lines flow via Miele USA distribution from Gütersloh OEM — typical 5-10 day LA-authorized service lead on common components. Post-Alabama ramp, some US-manufactured product lines may see 2-5 day typical lead; specific impact on MasterCool legacy-parts continues to emerge as the plant's product mix is confirmed. For current-production MasterCool + legacy-generation service, Gütersloh-sourced OEM continues as the primary parts channel.</p>
  </div></section>

